WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:05.171 --> 00:00:06.706 align:start size:94% position:6%
Joe Simpson, Jr.: Greetings
and a warm good evening

00:00:06.739 --> 00:00:08.608
from Southern California.

00:00:08.641 --> 00:00:10.710
My name is Joe Simpson, Jr.

00:00:10.743 --> 00:00:14.313
I'm the volunteer wrangler for
WordPress Accessibility Day.

00:00:14.346 --> 00:00:17.517 align:start size:81% position:19%
I'm also a WordCamp,
WordPress meetup,

00:00:17.550 --> 00:00:22.822
WordCamp organizer, community
and accessibility advocate.

00:00:22.855 --> 00:00:25.324 align:start size:84% position:16%
At my second
WordCamp Los Angeles,

00:00:25.357 --> 00:00:30.863
I saw this fiery ball of energy
and artistic-ness up on stage,

00:00:30.896 --> 00:00:33.566 align:start size:84% position:16%
presenting and
commanding the stage,

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:36.469 align:start size:84% position:16%
and I thought, "I
think I wanna do that.

00:00:36.502 --> 00:00:38.704
I wanna get up on
stage and speak."

00:00:38.737 --> 00:00:41.674 align:start size:94% position:6%
All these years later, it is
my sincere pleasure

00:00:41.707 --> 00:00:43.576
to introduce her to you.

00:00:43.876 --> 00:00:48.347
Okay, Alicia St. Rose began her
adventure with WordPress when

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:51.851
a UX friend offhandedly
suggested using the CMS

00:00:51.884 --> 00:00:54.187
for a mutual friend's website.

00:00:54.220 --> 00:00:56.756
That was over ten years ago
and the adventure has turned

00:00:56.789 --> 00:00:59.592
into a torrid love affair.

00:00:59.625 --> 00:01:02.061 align:start position:0%
Now she's a freelance developer,
exclusively powered by

00:01:02.094 --> 00:01:06.499
WordPress, and has yet to find
a limitation in her magical--in

00:01:06.532 --> 00:01:08.768
this magical piece of software.

00:01:08.801 --> 00:01:11.838
She is the owner, principal
designer, and developer at

00:01:11.871 --> 00:01:17.376 align:start size:97% position:3%
WP with Heart, a small agency
that employs one, so far.

00:01:17.409 --> 00:01:20.313 align:start size:94% position:6%
In addition to creating for
WordPress, she provides

00:01:20.346 --> 00:01:25.218 align:start size:97% position:3%
an online one-on-one coaching
for DIY website creators.

00:01:25.251 --> 00:01:29.222 align:start size:94% position:6%
She's also a creativity and
mind shift mentor,

00:01:29.255 --> 00:01:31.057
empowering people to
bust through their own

00:01:31.090 --> 00:01:34.127
limitations in order to
radically express their

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:40.867 align:start size:84% position:16%
authentic and creative
ideas and selves.

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:43.703 align:start size:97% position:3%
I'd love to introduce to
you, presenting "Adventures in

00:01:43.736 --> 00:01:47.640
Accessibility: How Embracing
Accessibility Made Me a Better

00:01:47.673 --> 00:01:50.143
Storyteller," Alicia St. Rose.

00:01:50.176 --> 00:01:52.378
Take it away.

00:01:52.411 --> 00:01:54.347 align:start size:88% position:13%
Alicia St. Rose: Hello.
Hello, everyone.

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:58.551 align:start size:84% position:16%
Thank you so much
for that introduction.

00:01:58.584 --> 00:02:01.387 align:start size:88% position:13%
I'm just really touched.
Wow.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:04.790
So, I wanna make sure that
all the technical aspects

00:02:04.823 --> 00:02:06.392
are set up here.

00:02:06.425 --> 00:02:09.195 align:start size:91% position:9%
I'm getting ready to share
my screen, and I want

00:02:09.228 --> 00:02:12.265 align:start size:91% position:9%
the thumbs-up that you can
actually see it, okay?

00:02:12.298 --> 00:02:18.037 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, I don't want any--anything
to thwart our experience.

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:19.706
So, let me--

00:02:20.173 --> 00:02:25.811 align:start position:0% line:83%
Can everyone see the slide in--
for the slideshow?

00:02:25.844 --> 00:02:28.347 line:83%
I can't actually see any
thumbs-up, unfortunately,

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:31.284 align:start position:0% line:83%
because now I just see my
slideshow, so I'm gonna assume,

00:02:31.317 --> 00:02:34.220 align:start size:91% position:9% line:83%
no one's told me it's not
up, so here we go.

00:02:34.253 --> 00:02:37.390 align:start size:94% position:6% line:83%
So, "Adventures in
Accessibility: How Embracing

00:02:37.423 --> 00:02:44.330 line:83%
Accessibility Made Me
a Better Storyteller."

00:02:44.363 --> 00:02:48.701 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, every story starts with
"once upon a time," and so the

00:02:48.734 --> 00:02:52.305 align:start size:94% position:6%
story has to start with
that as well, and I'm going

00:02:52.338 --> 00:02:56.342 align:start position:0%
to go back to the not-so-distant
past with my story.

00:02:56.375 --> 00:03:00.446 align:start position:0%
I'm going to go back to
January 1, 2020, when I woke up

00:03:00.479 --> 00:03:05.151
on that day excited about what
this year was going to bring.

00:03:05.184 --> 00:03:07.820 align:start size:94% position:6%
It was gonna be
different, I could feel it,

00:03:07.853 --> 00:03:12.458 align:start size:97% position:3%
but I had no idea how
different it was going to be.

00:03:12.491 --> 00:03:16.696
And so, in March,
things drastically

00:03:16.729 --> 00:03:18.431
changed around the world.

00:03:18.464 --> 00:03:22.535 align:start position:0%
I mean, they were certainly
changing unbeknownst to a lot of

00:03:22.568 --> 00:03:26.138 align:start size:97% position:3%
us on this Western Hemisphere,
and then they changed

00:03:26.171 --> 00:03:28.040
drastically for
the entire world.

00:03:28.073 --> 00:03:34.680 align:start size:97% position:3%
And in that time, within that
time, technology seems to

00:03:34.713 --> 00:03:39.285
have had a renaissance and
a bursting forth into some

00:03:39.318 --> 00:03:43.522
expansiveness that I've
not seen in my lifetime.

00:03:43.555 --> 00:03:49.762 align:start position:0%
And with that I--it brought some
limitations that were always

00:03:49.795 --> 00:03:54.066
there on the web and
in technological areas,

00:03:54.099 --> 00:03:59.071 align:start size:84% position:16%
but they became
increasingly obvious.

00:03:59.104 --> 00:04:04.176 align:start position:0%
So, I will tell you a little bit
about me before we get

00:04:04.209 --> 00:04:07.046 align:start size:84% position:16%
into the accessibility
adventure.

00:04:07.079 --> 00:04:13.152 align:start position:0%
So, I started my web development
career by wanting to make my

00:04:13.185 --> 00:04:18.090 align:start position:0%
blogger website look better
when I moved over to WordPress,

00:04:18.123 --> 00:04:24.196 align:start position:0%
and so I spent an entire
night trying to find out what a

00:04:24.229 --> 00:04:28.768
hashtag and three Cs meant when
there was a hashtag and six Cs,

00:04:28.801 --> 00:04:29.969
and I couldn't make it work.

00:04:30.002 --> 00:04:33.673
And I didn't understand it,
and so I ended up going to a

00:04:33.706 --> 00:04:36.475
bookstore at 6--you know,
I stayed up till 6 a.m.,

00:04:36.508 --> 00:04:39.378 align:start position:0%
and I rushed off to a bookstore
as soon as it opened in the

00:04:39.411 --> 00:04:41.747 align:start size:97% position:3%
morning, and I came out with a
book called "The Headfirst

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:44.850
Guide to HTML and CSS."

00:04:44.883 --> 00:04:49.188 align:start size:91% position:9%
It jump-started my
career as a web developer.

00:04:49.221 --> 00:04:51.157
I had no idea that I
would be into that,

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:53.059
that I would turn into a geek.

00:04:53.092 --> 00:04:58.064 align:start size:94% position:6%
I actually was a fine
artist up until that moment,

00:04:58.097 --> 00:05:02.468
and my drawing table got dusty
as I realized that part--the

00:05:02.501 --> 00:05:04.603
other part of my mind
really wanted to learn

00:05:04.636 --> 00:05:06.639
something every single day.

00:05:06.672 --> 00:05:09.775
And every single day I did when
I was doing web development,

00:05:09.808 --> 00:05:12.378 align:start position:0%
especially as I was
learning, so I was self-taught.

00:05:12.411 --> 00:05:16.415
I learned from books, and
I'm very detail-oriented,

00:05:16.448 --> 00:05:19.618 align:start size:81% position:19%
so every time
something came up, I

00:05:19.651 --> 00:05:21.120
would do a little Google search.

00:05:21.153 --> 00:05:23.456 align:start size:81% position:19%
We all went to
Google U to do this.

00:05:23.489 --> 00:05:26.359
That's what we do now, and
there's nothing--there's no

00:05:26.392 --> 00:05:28.160
shame in that, by the way.

00:05:28.193 --> 00:05:32.431
So, I, over the years, I became
better and better at the web

00:05:32.464 --> 00:05:36.535
development thing, and then
I found out about WordCamps.

00:05:36.568 --> 00:05:41.273
And had no idea these existed
and went to my first one in

00:05:41.306 --> 00:05:46.379
Orange County, 2014,
and I found my people.

00:05:46.412 --> 00:05:48.514 align:start size:81% position:19%
And it was an
amazing experience.

00:05:48.547 --> 00:05:51.484 align:start size:97% position:3%
And I'm the type of
person that wants to inspire,

00:05:51.517 --> 00:05:55.755
to empower, and teach, and when
I realized there was two days of

00:05:55.788 --> 00:06:01.394
that, that people could show up
and just talk about WordPress

00:06:01.427 --> 00:06:03.529 align:start size:88% position:13%
and how it inspired
them and how they could,

00:06:03.562 --> 00:06:06.399
like, impart that information
to others and kinda grow the

00:06:06.432 --> 00:06:08.467
community, and I was hooked.

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:13.005
And so then I went from
the WordCamps to meetups,

00:06:13.038 --> 00:06:15.274
so I had my own meetup
here in Santa Barbara.

00:06:15.307 --> 00:06:20.579 align:start size:94% position:6%
I have it currently, and
it's the South Central Coast

00:06:20.612 --> 00:06:23.282
WordPress Adventure Group.

00:06:23.315 --> 00:06:26.218
Found out that the Central Coast
all--goes all the way to Santa

00:06:26.251 --> 00:06:29.088 align:start size:91% position:9%
Cruz, and I was not
willing to drive that far,

00:06:29.121 --> 00:06:30.623
so it's South Central.

00:06:30.656 --> 00:06:33.459
So now, you see I
am detail-oriented,

00:06:33.492 --> 00:06:37.830
to that point that I can't
even geographically mix.

00:06:37.863 --> 00:06:42.501 align:start size:84% position:16%
So, in one of my
meetups very recently,

00:06:42.534 --> 00:06:45.604 align:start size:88% position:13%
within this year of
2020, a woman showed up,

00:06:45.637 --> 00:06:47.573
and her name is
Sumner Davenport.

00:06:47.606 --> 00:06:52.044 align:start size:94% position:6%
And you
will--you'll meet her later,

00:06:52.077 --> 00:06:55.381 align:start size:88% position:13%
very shortly, if you
haven't met her already.

00:06:55.414 --> 00:06:56.749 align:start size:84% position:16%
And she showed up
at one of my meetups,

00:06:56.782 --> 00:07:03.289 align:start size:97% position:3%
and she just discussed
something about accessibility.

00:07:03.322 --> 00:07:06.091
And I had heard about
it, and I thought,

00:07:06.124 --> 00:07:07.426
"Yeah, I know what that is.

00:07:07.459 --> 00:07:10.696
It means that, you know,
people should be able to,

00:07:10.729 --> 00:07:14.533
you know, read whatever is on
the web and not have it hidden

00:07:14.566 --> 00:07:19.205
from them, that in my vague--my
vague idea of it is that they

00:07:19.238 --> 00:07:21.474
just need to get
the information.

00:07:21.507 --> 00:07:24.043
And that's vitally important."

00:07:24.076 --> 00:07:28.013 align:start size:97% position:3%
I didn't think their
experience had to be the same.

00:07:28.046 --> 00:07:31.083
That night, when she showed
up to my WordPress meetup,

00:07:31.116 --> 00:07:34.320
she informed me but--that the
experience being the same is

00:07:34.353 --> 00:07:38.157
actually essential because it
really isn't fair that someone

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:40.192
can't enjoy the same experience.

00:07:40.225 --> 00:07:42.628
Not only that, it was
violating civil rights,

00:07:42.661 --> 00:07:45.064
and I was like, "Whoa!"

00:07:45.097 --> 00:07:48.534
I was totally like, "Whoa!"

00:07:48.567 --> 00:07:54.173
And at the--as she was talking,
I literally went to a client's

00:07:54.206 --> 00:07:57.610
website and took off what is
called an overlay that I had

00:07:57.643 --> 00:08:01.347 align:start position:0%
thought I was so crafty putting
on his site to protect him,

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:04.783
but I'd actually
done the opposite.

00:08:04.816 --> 00:08:07.386 align:start size:84% position:16%
And in that
moment I realized, A,

00:08:07.419 --> 00:08:10.356
I had a goldmine at
my WordPress meetup,

00:08:10.389 --> 00:08:11.590
I was just like, "Oh, wow.

00:08:11.624 --> 00:08:16.495
I just totally fell into the
right company with this one."

00:08:16.528 --> 00:08:21.800
And then, from that moment on I
realized that there was a lot

00:08:21.833 --> 00:08:25.371 align:start size:91% position:9%
more to this web
thing that I didn't know,

00:08:25.404 --> 00:08:30.342 align:start size:88% position:13%
and then I
started to feel really,

00:08:30.375 --> 00:08:34.079
really kind of heavy about it.

00:08:34.112 --> 00:08:36.782
And I thought, "Shoot.

00:08:36.815 --> 00:08:38.551
This is more work
than I thought,

00:08:38.584 --> 00:08:41.654
and I'm like feeling a little
bit overwhelmed about this.

00:08:41.687 --> 00:08:45.324
I don't know if I'm gonna
be able to pull this off."

00:08:45.357 --> 00:08:49.595
And it just became this--now
it seemed where I was very,

00:08:49.628 --> 00:08:53.465
very detail-oriented and very
careful about what I did with

00:08:53.498 --> 00:09:02.074
web, that now I had gone back
several meters to the starting

00:09:02.107 --> 00:09:04.243
line of, "Oh, my gosh.

00:09:04.276 --> 00:09:07.279 align:start size:97% position:3%
There's all this accessibility
stuff that I don't know.

00:09:07.312 --> 00:09:09.281 align:start size:84% position:16%
And I'm gonna have
to catch up with that.

00:09:09.314 --> 00:09:11.050
And I'm in the midst
of a project right now,

00:09:11.083 --> 00:09:14.053
and I know right now that some
of the stuff that I'm doing even

00:09:14.086 --> 00:09:16.188
on that site is not accessible.

00:09:16.221 --> 00:09:17.556
And I haven't even
launched that yet,

00:09:17.589 --> 00:09:19.992
and I'm just about
ready to do it."

00:09:20.025 --> 00:09:25.264 align:start size:91% position:9%
So, I had to
actually let that soak in.

00:09:25.297 --> 00:09:30.035
I had to realize that, at some
point, is gotta put the big-girl

00:09:30.068 --> 00:09:33.706
panties on, and I had to
realize that this is a part

00:09:33.739 --> 00:09:37.409
of what a website entails.

00:09:37.442 --> 00:09:41.780
It can't actually
be an afterthought.

00:09:41.813 --> 00:09:46.785
It can't actually be something
that you can put in later or

00:09:46.818 --> 00:09:50.656 align:start size:91% position:9%
maybe someone won't
notice, and so I decided,

00:09:50.689 --> 00:09:52.758 align:start size:81% position:19%
"I'm just gonna
have to embrace it.

00:09:52.791 --> 00:09:57.529
Take a deep breath and
just learn what you can,

00:09:57.562 --> 00:10:00.699 align:start size:78% position:22%
and the people
will fall in line.

00:10:00.732 --> 00:10:02.601
They will show up to help."

00:10:02.634 --> 00:10:05.070
And Sumner kept
coming to my

00:10:05.103 --> 00:10:06.405
meetup, which was awesome.

00:10:06.438 --> 00:10:08.207
I started going to her meetup.

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:11.443
Then wonderful, wonderful
presentations by people.

00:10:11.476 --> 00:10:16.048
Some of them you've
seen already today,

00:10:16.081 --> 00:10:22.287
Meryl and several other, like,
amazing presentations put on by

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:27.860
the San Fernando Valley Meetup,
which is accessibility-based.

00:10:27.893 --> 00:10:32.464 align:start position:0%
And I realized this was actually
gonna be fun, and that there

00:10:32.497 --> 00:10:35.534 align:start position:0%
were so many people on board and
so passionate about helping

00:10:35.567 --> 00:10:41.607
other people get access to the
Internet, especially in a time

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:46.145 align:start position:0%
right now where they're inside,
quarantined in some cases,

00:10:46.178 --> 00:10:50.883
and in a lot of cases--because
some people who are diff-abled,

00:10:50.916 --> 00:10:53.752 align:start size:94% position:6%
or disabled, if they
would wanna be called that,

00:10:53.785 --> 00:10:57.656
have health issues that they
don't actually wanna be exposed

00:10:57.689 --> 00:11:00.426
to other viruses, so they were
really--there's a lot of people

00:11:00.459 --> 00:11:04.697 align:start size:88% position:13%
who are really depending
on the Internet to be

00:11:04.730 --> 00:11:06.265
their window to the world.

00:11:06.298 --> 00:11:10.602 align:start size:97% position:3%
And when I found out that
only 2% of that could actually

00:11:10.635 --> 00:11:13.472 align:start size:81% position:19%
facilitate that
experience for them,

00:11:13.505 --> 00:11:17.276 align:start size:94% position:6%
I was even more disappointed
and even deeply was

00:11:17.309 --> 00:11:19.845 align:start size:94% position:6%
disappointed because I
realized that if it was 2%,

00:11:19.878 --> 00:11:22.848
they were probably only
the government websites.

00:11:22.881 --> 00:11:25.117 align:start size:97% position:3%
And that's not gonna be--I
know you wanna get information

00:11:25.150 --> 00:11:27.186 align:start size:78% position:22%
for--you know,
during a pandemic,

00:11:27.219 --> 00:11:28.787 align:start size:84% position:16%
but sometimes you
wanna be entertained,

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:31.190 align:start size:91% position:9%
and you wanna go shopping,
and you wanna buy food,

00:11:31.223 --> 00:11:32.558
and you wanna do
all these things.

00:11:32.591 --> 00:11:35.861 align:start position:0%
And so, I realized, "Wow,
I don't wanna be a part of that.

00:11:35.894 --> 00:11:41.333
I wanna be a part of bringing
joy to someone who is surfing

00:11:41.366 --> 00:11:43.368
the web, and they've gone
through site after site,

00:11:43.401 --> 00:11:45.404
and then they land on the one
that I've made for somebody."

00:11:45.437 --> 00:11:47.673 align:start size:78% position:22%
And my clients are
benefiting too

00:11:47.706 --> 00:11:50.876 align:start size:91% position:9%
because now
everyone can have access.

00:11:50.909 --> 00:11:54.713 align:start position:0%
And so, I decided--after I
decided that I was gonna embrace

00:11:54.746 --> 00:11:58.083
this, I realized that there were
some gifts in this and that they

00:11:58.116 --> 00:12:07.359
improved my actual--my value and
the way that I tell stories for

00:12:07.392 --> 00:12:13.632
my clients, because building
a website is not--it's not

00:12:13.665 --> 00:12:16.702
some, what's the word?

00:12:16.735 --> 00:12:19.304 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's not a basic
or vanilla task, okay?

00:12:19.337 --> 00:12:22.341 align:start size:91% position:9%
You are telling someone's
story when you put

00:12:22.374 --> 00:12:23.776
a website up for them.

00:12:23.809 --> 00:12:28.046 align:start size:94% position:6%
It's not, "I'm gonna go drag
something around and make

00:12:28.079 --> 00:12:29.481
it look pretty for you."

00:12:29.514 --> 00:12:34.386
It is how are they--you
expressing their inner

00:12:34.419 --> 00:12:37.656 align:start size:97% position:3%
motivations and passion to
the audience that they want to

00:12:37.689 --> 00:12:43.695
receive that, and so it is
like storytelling for them,

00:12:43.728 --> 00:12:47.399 align:start size:97% position:3%
or even movie
scripting, or whatever it is.

00:12:47.432 --> 00:12:51.537
It's not a basic tech task.

00:12:51.570 --> 00:12:54.273 align:start size:97% position:3%
There's a lot of
humanity in making a website,

00:12:54.306 --> 00:12:59.211
and so this aspect of adding
accessibility even brings more

00:12:59.244 --> 00:13:05.017
humanity to it, because it's
actually a--I don't know the

00:13:05.050 --> 00:13:08.120
word I'm looking for.

00:13:08.153 --> 00:13:14.827
It's an honorable thing to do,
to bring access to those who do

00:13:14.860 --> 00:13:17.229
not have it at the moment.

00:13:17.262 --> 00:13:22.568
So, one of the things that I
did learn on my adventure to

00:13:22.601 --> 00:13:29.541
this storytelling is that the
sensitivity to others' needs is

00:13:29.574 --> 00:13:34.313
actually in the forefront of
every decision that I make when

00:13:34.346 --> 00:13:38.116
I'm building the website.

00:13:38.149 --> 00:13:41.253
Oh, my goodness.
Let me cancel that.

00:13:41.286 --> 00:13:43.455
Now I can see myself.
Okay, so, I'm sorry.

00:13:43.488 --> 00:13:46.859
Some wild thing just
happened on my screen,

00:13:46.892 --> 00:13:48.727
and it took me aback.

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:51.129
A bunch of things just opened
up, and I'm gonna close this.

00:13:51.162 --> 00:13:53.198
Okay, so I'm back.

00:13:53.231 --> 00:13:58.737 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, the sensitivity to others'
needs became the permeating

00:13:58.770 --> 00:14:02.341
intention to everything
that I did on the site.

00:14:02.374 --> 00:14:05.444 align:start size:94% position:6%
And it wasn't just the
sensitivity to the visitors'

00:14:05.477 --> 00:14:07.713
needs, which has always
been the thing that was

00:14:07.746 --> 00:14:10.148
more important to me.

00:14:10.181 --> 00:14:12.384
I did not ignore
the clients' needs.

00:14:12.417 --> 00:14:15.821 align:start size:97% position:3%
They always had these specific
things that they wanted.

00:14:15.854 --> 00:14:19.725
They always had these design or
aesthetic ideas that they needed

00:14:19.758 --> 00:14:21.827
to have on the website.

00:14:21.860 --> 00:14:23.795
It was kinda like one of those
cooking shows where they give

00:14:23.828 --> 00:14:29.701
you some Chiclets, a
bagel, and a Pop-Tart,

00:14:29.734 --> 00:14:32.271 align:start size:84% position:16%
and you got to make up
a five-course meal

00:14:32.304 --> 00:14:33.539 align:start size:84% position:16%
out of that, you know
what I'm saying?

00:14:33.572 --> 00:14:35.841
Like, sometimes that happens,
and you get Comic Sans and you

00:14:35.874 --> 00:14:39.578
get fuchsia, and you're like, "I
got to work this out somehow,"

00:14:39.611 --> 00:14:42.814
and so that's where the
creativity comes from.

00:14:42.847 --> 00:14:47.319
Your creativity comes
from, like, what you

00:14:47.352 --> 00:14:49.488
would sometimes call a
limitation, but it's not.

00:14:49.521 --> 00:14:52.190
It's a parameter which you
work in, and it actually

00:14:52.223 --> 00:14:55.327 align:start size:97% position:3%
creates--it makes you more
creative, so my sensitivity to

00:14:55.360 --> 00:14:58.096 align:start size:97% position:3%
others' needs was something I
learned, and it became,

00:14:58.129 --> 00:15:03.368 align:start position:0%
actually, this fun way of
dealing with content and layout.

00:15:03.401 --> 00:15:05.671 align:start size:91% position:9%
It's like, "So, if someone
needed to tab through

00:15:05.704 --> 00:15:06.905
this, what do we have to do?"

00:15:06.939 --> 00:15:11.410
And then, to make sure that
you're happy with having this

00:15:11.443 --> 00:15:14.346 align:start size:91% position:9%
kind of cool hero image
with only--we can do this.

00:15:14.379 --> 00:15:15.814
We can merge the two.

00:15:15.847 --> 00:15:18.383 align:start position:0%
We can make it work, so the
sensitivity to others' needs was

00:15:18.416 --> 00:15:20.352
really, really important.

00:15:20.385 --> 00:15:24.723
Also, as--whoops.

00:15:24.756 --> 00:15:34.199
As I got deeper and deeper
into the accessibility--oops.

00:15:34.232 --> 00:15:37.536
I skipped a slide.

00:15:37.569 --> 00:15:42.140 align:start size:69% position:31%
There it is.
Okay.

00:15:42.173 --> 00:15:44.343
I have a delay.

00:15:44.376 --> 00:15:47.713
Okay, as I got better--as I
got more and more into the

00:15:47.746 --> 00:15:51.750 align:start size:91% position:9%
accessibility and
getting more information,

00:15:51.783 --> 00:15:56.655 align:start position:0%
my education of even web
development became--got better,

00:15:56.688 --> 00:15:58.390
and then improving skills.

00:15:58.423 --> 00:16:01.460 align:start size:97% position:3%
And every time I learned
something and I imparted it to

00:16:01.493 --> 00:16:05.197 align:start position:0%
my clients, it was--the fun part
was actually explaining this

00:16:05.230 --> 00:16:09.334 align:start position:0%
stuff to my clients and
explaining how important it was.

00:16:09.367 --> 00:16:15.474
And then, in my experience, the
people I've told have felt the

00:16:15.507 --> 00:16:19.077 align:start size:81% position:19%
levity and the
importance of this.

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:23.148
They realize that it's
to be taken seriously,

00:16:23.181 --> 00:16:28.587
and they actually feel honored
that they could be a part of

00:16:28.620 --> 00:16:32.090 align:start size:97% position:3%
making the web better, so--and
actually relieved

00:16:32.123 --> 00:16:34.393
that I care about it too.

00:16:34.426 --> 00:16:37.329
So, there are clients out there
who really want people to help

00:16:37.362 --> 00:16:42.834
them with this kind of stuff,
and so--and if they do run into

00:16:42.867 --> 00:16:46.838
developers or people who
think it's not important,

00:16:46.871 --> 00:16:49.608 align:start size:81% position:19%
part of the
client's kinda like

00:16:49.641 --> 00:16:50.809
feeling a little
uneasy about that,

00:16:50.842 --> 00:16:54.546 align:start position:0%
because it's their job and their
business that's on the line.

00:16:54.579 --> 00:16:59.418 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, you won't get--I don't
really get a negative response

00:16:59.451 --> 00:17:01.620
when I bring up the
accessibility stuff.

00:17:01.653 --> 00:17:04.022 align:start position:0%
I get surprise because they
didn't realize how important it

00:17:04.055 --> 00:17:08.260
has gotten, but I do not
get any kind of negatives.

00:17:08.293 --> 00:17:10.662 align:start size:84% position:16%
So, there was the
education and skills.

00:17:10.695 --> 00:17:14.499 align:start size:94% position:6%
Of course, it's something
that makes you more valuable

00:17:14.532 --> 00:17:17.202
as a web developer.

00:17:17.235 --> 00:17:21.640
Also, it became--I became a
better observer of my world

00:17:21.673 --> 00:17:28.180
because now it was a user
experience not in the tech

00:17:28.213 --> 00:17:34.519
sense but just in a sense that
was more global or universal.

00:17:34.552 --> 00:17:38.023 align:start position:0%
You talk about the journey of
the client through your website.

00:17:38.056 --> 00:17:41.526
Now you have to think about
the journey of someone who,

00:17:41.559 --> 00:17:44.096
let's just put it this way,
broke both their wrists and

00:17:44.129 --> 00:17:45.364
can't use the keyboard.

00:17:45.397 --> 00:17:51.103
It's not necessarily someone who
is paralyzed and can never walk

00:17:51.136 --> 00:17:52.838
again or use their arms.

00:17:52.871 --> 00:17:56.775 align:start size:94% position:6%
Some of these things are
temporary and there might be

00:17:56.808 --> 00:18:01.313
very, very--a very serious
or important need to get to a

00:18:01.346 --> 00:18:04.616
website in those six months or
four months that you have two

00:18:04.649 --> 00:18:05.850
casts on your arms.

00:18:05.884 --> 00:18:12.457
So, when they say a percentage
of people using the web who have

00:18:12.490 --> 00:18:16.094 align:start size:94% position:6%
accessibility issues, I'm
not sure they even count the

00:18:16.127 --> 00:18:18.697 align:start size:97% position:3%
temporary people that are
flowing in and out of that at

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:22.134
any given time, so
you have to--so,

00:18:22.167 --> 00:18:25.504 align:start position:0%
you became--not only did I
become a better observer of the

00:18:25.537 --> 00:18:28.807
world in that way, but also the
information and content that my

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:31.276 align:start size:88% position:13%
client was
putting on the website.

00:18:31.309 --> 00:18:34.179 align:start size:84% position:16%
I had one client
who, he is an artist,

00:18:34.212 --> 00:18:36.648
a veneer artist, and he
had a lot of art pieces,

00:18:36.681 --> 00:18:41.586
and he was using these prime
symbols for inches and feet.

00:18:41.619 --> 00:18:44.789
And I had to go investigate
whether the screen reader,

00:18:44.822 --> 00:18:49.828 align:start position:0%
all of them, would pick that up,
and it didn't seem likely the

00:18:49.861 --> 00:18:53.698 align:start size:91% position:9%
way we were designing
everything, so I actually

00:18:53.731 --> 00:18:58.069 align:start size:94% position:6%
revamped that whole thing to
say "inches" and "feet,"

00:18:58.102 --> 00:19:00.105 align:start size:97% position:3%
they're actually
spelled out--and centimeters.

00:19:00.138 --> 00:19:05.210
And in the course of that, I
also discovered a lot about his

00:19:05.243 --> 00:19:07.212 align:start size:78% position:22%
veneer work and
what he was doing.

00:19:07.245 --> 00:19:12.784
And also in the content,
there were things that were

00:19:12.817 --> 00:19:16.021
alphabetized, like
common names of wood,

00:19:16.054 --> 00:19:18.223
that are never to
be alphabetized,

00:19:18.256 --> 00:19:20.292 align:start size:91% position:9%
and a screen reader
would have taken that as,

00:19:20.325 --> 00:19:25.463
"Oh, we're talking about a
proper noun called Pine.

00:19:25.496 --> 00:19:26.998
Maybe it's a city or something."

00:19:27.031 --> 00:19:29.267 align:start size:75% position:25%
But you can't do
that, so we

00:19:29.300 --> 00:19:30.602
learned--I learned
things like that.

00:19:30.635 --> 00:19:32.537 align:start size:91% position:9%
I was able to
explain it to the client,

00:19:32.570 --> 00:19:35.207
was able to explain to 'em
that a genus and a species,

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:36.541
you only alphabetize the genus.

00:19:36.574 --> 00:19:43.415 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, I learned all these
things by being attentive to

00:19:43.448 --> 00:19:47.185
accessibility, and so
it's not really dry.

00:19:47.218 --> 00:19:48.687
It's really--it's
almost kinda fun.

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:54.326 align:start position:0%
It's like having a lesson in
life or what your client does at

00:19:54.359 --> 00:19:58.296
all times, and when your client
feels like you're that invested

00:19:58.329 --> 00:20:01.066 align:start size:94% position:6%
or you're that knowledgeable
about what they do,

00:20:01.099 --> 00:20:04.135 align:start size:78% position:22%
they actually
value you more too

00:20:04.168 --> 00:20:07.372 align:start size:91% position:9%
and they feel very safe
with you working with them

00:20:07.405 --> 00:20:11.142
because they know that you
care about their business,

00:20:11.175 --> 00:20:13.278 align:start size:88% position:13%
sometimes almost as much
as they care about it

00:20:13.311 --> 00:20:15.580
themselves, or sometimes more.

00:20:15.613 --> 00:20:18.516
So, that was one of the
things, became a better

00:20:18.549 --> 00:20:20.518
observer of the world.

00:20:20.551 --> 00:20:22.654 align:start size:94% position:6%
And, finally, of course,
this is what this is called.

00:20:22.687 --> 00:20:24.489
I became a better storyteller.

00:20:24.522 --> 00:20:26.424
Like, I could tell
their story better,

00:20:26.457 --> 00:20:33.665 align:start position:0%
and I could--accessibility
helped me--carved a way for--it

00:20:33.698 --> 00:20:38.336
carved a path for me to follow.

00:20:38.369 --> 00:20:41.206
It was--it almost kinda
reined everything in.

00:20:41.239 --> 00:20:43.375 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, sometimes when
there's content, it's like,

00:20:43.408 --> 00:20:44.809
"What do I say and
how do I say it?"

00:20:44.842 --> 00:20:46.711
But when you're thinking,
"Well, how do I say it

00:20:46.744 --> 00:20:48.747
so everyone will get access?"

00:20:48.780 --> 00:20:53.752
it almost makes it easier to
create the content, so I became

00:20:53.785 --> 00:20:57.422
a better storyteller for what
my client was trying to do.

00:20:57.455 --> 00:21:03.461
And that's what everyone is
trying to do on the Internet.

00:21:03.494 --> 00:21:05.497 align:start size:84% position:16%
They're trying to
tell their own story,

00:21:05.530 --> 00:21:09.668
and so you wanna be that person
to facilitate that for them,

00:21:09.701 --> 00:21:12.304
not necessarily just
give them a website.

00:21:12.337 --> 00:21:14.539
That's not what we do.

00:21:14.572 --> 00:21:17.309 align:start position:0%
You developers out there, we
just don't give people websites.

00:21:17.342 --> 00:21:19.544
It's an experience.

00:21:19.577 --> 00:21:23.615 align:start size:91% position:9%
It really is, and
so--and it's their story.

00:21:23.648 --> 00:21:29.120 align:start size:81% position:19%
And--every story
has--there's an end.

00:21:29.153 --> 00:21:34.092
There is an end to a story, but
the end is just the beginning in

00:21:34.125 --> 00:21:37.729 align:start size:81% position:19%
this one because you
are never going

00:21:37.762 --> 00:21:39.464
to stop learning this stuff.

00:21:39.497 --> 00:21:42.167 align:start size:88% position:13%
There's always
gonna be something new,

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:44.069 align:start size:88% position:13%
some new
technology coming along.

00:21:44.102 --> 00:21:47.572
It was like that before
even accessibilities

00:21:47.605 --> 00:21:49.207
became a big thing.

00:21:49.240 --> 00:21:52.243
If you thought you were gonna
stop learning because you were

00:21:52.276 --> 00:21:54.546 align:start position:0%
doing, you know, web stuff, that
there was one point where you

00:21:54.579 --> 00:21:58.550 align:start size:88% position:13%
were gonna Google
your last code snippet,

00:21:58.583 --> 00:22:01.152
that time was never coming.

00:22:01.185 --> 00:22:06.191
There was always an opportunity
to learn, and right now, anyone

00:22:06.224 --> 00:22:09.627
who's been watching any of these
sessions and getting any of this

00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:12.297
information that's been
dispensed throughout the

00:22:12.330 --> 00:22:15.133 align:start size:94% position:6%
day--valuable, valuable
information--you're learning

00:22:15.166 --> 00:22:18.670 align:start size:88% position:13%
some really
amazing, amazing tools.

00:22:18.703 --> 00:22:22.374
That you are ready to go out to
the world and make it a better

00:22:22.407 --> 00:22:27.345
place for other people to get to
the web and also to bring more

00:22:27.378 --> 00:22:30.348
value to clients, so this
is just the beginning of

00:22:30.381 --> 00:22:32.584
everything, and just
the beginning for me

00:22:32.617 --> 00:22:37.055 align:start size:84% position:16%
because, to be honest,
I have not taken

00:22:37.088 --> 00:22:39.758
any certification courses.

00:22:39.791 --> 00:22:44.562 align:start position:0%
All of this is from
meetups and working on websites.

00:22:44.595 --> 00:22:48.099 align:start size:88% position:13%
And every, you
know, step that I take,

00:22:48.132 --> 00:22:51.302 align:start size:91% position:9%
I do a little bit
of a search and go, "Hmm.

00:22:51.335 --> 00:22:53.471 align:start size:91% position:9%
Is that appropriate?"
and then I learn that way.

00:22:53.504 --> 00:22:56.541 align:start size:91% position:9%
So, what I wanted to
instill in people who felt

00:22:56.574 --> 00:22:59.444 align:start size:94% position:6%
overwhelmed--because even
during some of the sessions,

00:22:59.477 --> 00:23:01.346
I saw some chat information.

00:23:01.379 --> 00:23:05.150 align:start size:94% position:6%
I saw some very informative
chat about people--you

00:23:05.183 --> 00:23:06.484
know who you are too.

00:23:06.517 --> 00:23:08.486
We joked about it.

00:23:08.519 --> 00:23:11.389 align:start size:97% position:3%
Wanted to give up their
career because this looked too

00:23:11.422 --> 00:23:14.426 align:start position:0%
overwhelming, and I know exactly
how the person felt because

00:23:14.459 --> 00:23:16.127 align:start size:84% position:16%
that's how I felt
in the beginning too,

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:17.695 align:start size:78% position:22%
but it's not
really like that.

00:23:17.728 --> 00:23:20.732 align:start size:91% position:9%
It's like--it's more like,
"Oh, my god.

00:23:20.765 --> 00:23:25.570 align:start position:0%
Look at this horizon just opened
up for you to help people."

00:23:25.603 --> 00:23:28.807 align:start size:88% position:13%
And all of these
people, talented people,

00:23:28.840 --> 00:23:32.677
who are jumping on board and
sharing their knowledge and

00:23:32.710 --> 00:23:35.079 align:start size:94% position:6%
really taking it seriously,
and right now is

00:23:35.112 --> 00:23:36.681
just the beginning of that.

00:23:36.714 --> 00:23:40.318 align:start position:0%
And if 2% of the web is
accessible, that means 98% of it

00:23:40.351 --> 00:23:43.154 align:start size:97% position:3%
is just flapping out there in
the wind, low-hanging

00:23:43.187 --> 00:23:46.090 align:start size:94% position:6%
fruit ready for
you to just go and grab it.

00:23:46.123 --> 00:23:48.359 align:start size:84% position:16%
There was nothing
Jerry Jones taught to

00:23:48.392 --> 00:23:50.795
get you started, okay?

00:23:50.828 --> 00:23:54.566
I'm serious, you could tell your
clients how to put their content

00:23:54.599 --> 00:23:58.403 align:start size:97% position:3%
in correctly, and that'll save
almost two-thirds of their

00:23:58.436 --> 00:24:03.608
issues of any kind
of accessibility,

00:24:03.641 --> 00:24:04.776
you know, red flags.

00:24:04.809 --> 00:24:08.279 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, it's just the beginning,
it's awesome, and so what

00:24:08.312 --> 00:24:12.450 align:start size:97% position:3%
I wanted to do now--first
of all, that's my last slide.

00:24:12.483 --> 00:24:14.486
That is my name.

00:24:14.519 --> 00:24:16.287
"St." is not a middle name.

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:19.324 align:start position:0%
My last name is St. Rose, so
it causes a lot of problems with

00:24:19.357 --> 00:24:22.527
computers and fields and stuff.

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:24.829 align:start size:94% position:6%
I'm often called
"Strose," but that's not it.

00:24:24.862 --> 00:24:28.032 align:start size:97% position:3%
You can find me on
Twitter with IntrepidRealist,

00:24:28.065 --> 00:24:32.470
and my website is
wpwithheart.com,

00:24:32.503 --> 00:24:36.107
and what I do there is I do--I
coach people one on one how to

00:24:36.140 --> 00:24:38.409
put their websites up, but we
don't even start building a

00:24:38.442 --> 00:24:41.446
website for a while, 'cause no
one should until they know what

00:24:41.479 --> 00:24:43.848 align:start size:84% position:16%
they're doing and
why they're doing it.

00:24:43.881 --> 00:24:48.520
So, you can find me there, but
what I wanted to do was I wanted

00:24:48.553 --> 00:24:54.726 align:start position:0%
to demonstrate a few things that
I've done since that fateful

00:24:54.759 --> 00:24:58.696 align:start size:94% position:6%
meeting in that meetup, and
one of 'em is actually

00:24:58.729 --> 00:25:00.298
quite recent, so let's see.

00:25:00.331 --> 00:25:05.370
I'm gonna escape here, and
we're gonna move this over.

00:25:05.403 --> 00:25:07.071 align:start size:84% position:16%
I don't know
what's on the screen.

00:25:07.104 --> 00:25:14.579 align:start position:0%
Okay, so, I don't think you guys
need to see the Slack here.

00:25:14.612 --> 00:25:16.614
I'll close that.
Let me close that.

00:25:16.647 --> 00:25:18.416
One of the things
that happened--

00:25:18.449 --> 00:25:19.751
and this is fairly recent.

00:25:19.784 --> 00:25:23.021 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, there was a discussion.
I can't remember.

00:25:23.054 --> 00:25:26.090 align:start size:81% position:19%
Sorry, I was--I
should look this up.

00:25:26.123 --> 00:25:27.625 align:start size:84% position:16%
There was a wonderful
presentation

00:25:27.658 --> 00:25:29.260
by a woman from Florida.

00:25:29.293 --> 00:25:36.634
She was a UX designer, and she
talked about designing the UX

00:25:36.667 --> 00:25:38.336
with accessibility in mind.

00:25:38.369 --> 00:25:40.738
Like, before even a
designer comes in,

00:25:40.771 --> 00:25:47.078 align:start position:0%
she's laying out, you know,
the content, those whole things.

00:25:47.111 --> 00:25:50.582 align:start size:94% position:6%
Oh, my god, I can't remember
what they were called.

00:25:50.615 --> 00:25:52.317
Anyway, like, the main
content, the sidebar,

00:25:52.350 --> 00:25:54.319 align:start size:81% position:19%
and the footer,
and all that stuff,

00:25:54.352 --> 00:25:56.487 align:start size:84% position:16%
all that's
planned ahead of time,

00:25:56.520 --> 00:25:59.757
so going in and trying to drag
something around without having

00:25:59.790 --> 00:26:05.129
that planning is really not
the best way to go about it.

00:26:05.162 --> 00:26:08.800
So, one of the things that just
popped out for me from that talk

00:26:08.833 --> 00:26:11.669 align:start position:0%
and what I'm trying to
instill here is that if you're a

00:26:11.702 --> 00:26:15.273
developer and you think this is
a whole bunch of stuff you have

00:26:15.306 --> 00:26:19.677
to learn, just take one piece
at a time and implement it.

00:26:19.710 --> 00:26:23.247 align:start size:91% position:9%
So, what she told me--it's
during--in a shopping

00:26:23.280 --> 00:26:30.121
site--that it's better to have
the product image on the right

00:26:30.154 --> 00:26:34.225
because as someone comes through
the page, they're going to hit

00:26:34.258 --> 00:26:39.297 align:start size:91% position:9%
the content, the text
first as a screen reader.

00:26:39.330 --> 00:26:42.433 align:start position:0%
It's vital--more important to
hit that first than the picture,

00:26:42.466 --> 00:26:44.602
which is just an illustration
of what's gonna probably be

00:26:44.635 --> 00:26:47.338 align:start size:88% position:13%
described over here, and
so I managed to do

00:26:47.371 --> 00:26:49.173
that with WooCommerce.

00:26:49.206 --> 00:26:56.180 align:start size:94% position:6%
And not only does this
picture show up on the site,

00:26:56.213 --> 00:27:00.151 align:start position:0%
but it's actually the third
thing that shows up on the page.

00:27:00.184 --> 00:27:04.789 align:start position:0%
And I was able to use what's
called Flexbox and flex order to

00:27:04.822 --> 00:27:07.692 align:start size:84% position:16%
actually swap the
order of the picture.

00:27:07.725 --> 00:27:10.561 align:start position:0%
So, I moved it to its--the third
position, where it would

00:27:10.594 --> 00:27:15.333
have been at the bottom of
the page here, by swap--just

00:27:15.366 --> 00:27:18.436 align:start size:94% position:6%
changing the order in CSS to
make it show up second.

00:27:18.469 --> 00:27:20.138 align:start size:81% position:19%
But when a screen
reader goes through,

00:27:20.171 --> 00:27:23.107
a screen reader will
come through the title,

00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:26.611
all this information, and hit
even this before the picture,

00:27:26.644 --> 00:27:30.448
is something that they
hit with a screen reader.

00:27:30.481 --> 00:27:33.685
So, that was really,
really, really awesome

00:27:33.718 --> 00:27:38.556
to be able to do that, and it's
that one piece of information.

00:27:38.589 --> 00:27:41.492 align:start size:84% position:16%
And so, it wasn't like
I was overwhelmed

00:27:41.525 --> 00:27:43.127
about, "Oh, my god.

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:46.097
I--this whole WooCommerce
thing and accessibility."

00:27:46.130 --> 00:27:48.232 align:start size:88% position:13%
I'm like, "I'm just
gonna take that piece."

00:27:48.265 --> 00:27:49.667
Today, I learned something.

00:27:49.700 --> 00:27:51.636 align:start size:94% position:6%
This is a white
background and that's black,

00:27:51.669 --> 00:27:54.172
so I'm gonna gray that up.

00:27:54.205 --> 00:27:56.574 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, I'm just gonna go through
the--with the CSS,

00:27:56.607 --> 00:28:00.211
and I'm going to make the font a
little grayer instead of black

00:28:00.244 --> 00:28:03.414
on white because I just learned
that, in one of the sessions

00:28:03.447 --> 00:28:09.554 align:start position:0%
today, that people with certain
disabilities, the font will

00:28:09.587 --> 00:28:12.023
start moving around,
so I'm like, "Got it."

00:28:12.056 --> 00:28:14.192 align:start size:97% position:3%
It's not like I have to, like,
learn everything at once

00:28:14.225 --> 00:28:15.660
and then go off and build.

00:28:15.693 --> 00:28:18.096 align:start size:88% position:13%
And another one
that--this one happened,

00:28:18.129 --> 00:28:22.433
actually, quite a while
ago, at the beginning,

00:28:22.466 --> 00:28:30.074
with--when I first found
out about accessibility.

00:28:30.107 --> 00:28:35.379
This is the one I was talking
about with the veneer artist,

00:28:35.412 --> 00:28:40.118
and here's what I've ended up
doing with height and diameter.

00:28:40.151 --> 00:28:45.156 align:start position:0%
Before, it was just this string
of numbers with primes and

00:28:45.189 --> 00:28:48.392
double prime or whatever, and
you really didn't even know

00:28:48.425 --> 00:28:50.094
which one was height or length.

00:28:50.127 --> 00:28:52.463 align:start size:97% position:3%
And whoever did the
content in, the three people,

00:28:52.496 --> 00:28:54.665
I think, over the years
who put the content in,

00:28:54.698 --> 00:29:01.405
mixed those two up anyway, and
so what I ended up doing for him

00:29:01.438 --> 00:29:03.541
is--this is another thing too,

00:29:03.574 --> 00:29:11.249 align:start position:0%
you can actually corral the
client into being accessible by

00:29:11.282 --> 00:29:14.118 align:start size:84% position:16%
providing information
on the back end.

00:29:14.151 --> 00:29:17.155 align:start size:97% position:3%
I'm using something
called advanced custom fields,

00:29:17.188 --> 00:29:20.525
and it may sound like
some kinda geeky thing

00:29:20.558 --> 00:29:23.594
if you've never heard of it, but
once you get it under your belt

00:29:23.627 --> 00:29:25.496 align:start size:81% position:19%
there's plenty of
documentation on it.

00:29:25.529 --> 00:29:29.367 align:start size:78% position:22%
You just create
fields in the post

00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:33.304 align:start size:97% position:3%
that they're custom for--that
you want for your client,

00:29:33.337 --> 00:29:35.673 align:start size:91% position:9%
and then they're custom
to whatever they're doing,

00:29:35.706 --> 00:29:39.443 align:start position:0%
and so what I ended up was
making these different--you can

00:29:39.476 --> 00:29:42.313
just add the information here.

00:29:42.346 --> 00:29:46.684 align:start size:94% position:6%
And I explained to him
how to do it, how to write,

00:29:46.717 --> 00:29:50.021
and all he has to do is come
in--and anyone who's working.

00:29:50.054 --> 00:29:54.258
There's no mistaking
this unless they just

00:29:54.291 --> 00:29:55.760
don't read directions, okay?

00:29:55.793 --> 00:30:02.633
So that's, like, you can do
these things to help keep the

00:30:02.666 --> 00:30:05.736
content accessible because
that's what's gonna happen.

00:30:05.769 --> 00:30:09.607
You're gonna let the site go,
and then you'll come back maybe

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:15.346
a few weeks later, and it's not
really working out because the

00:30:15.379 --> 00:30:19.684 align:start size:97% position:3%
client wasn't educated on
headings and things like that.

00:30:19.717 --> 00:30:22.687 align:start size:88% position:13%
And this is not--what's
going on here too

00:30:22.720 --> 00:30:25.756
is--that clearly it does not
look like the Gutenberg editor.

00:30:25.789 --> 00:30:27.024
It is not.

00:30:27.057 --> 00:30:32.563
It is actually--this is a custom
post type that I created for his

00:30:32.596 --> 00:30:37.335
projects, and that's another
geek-level thing and not--that

00:30:37.368 --> 00:30:38.736 align:start size:94% position:6%
is not even
difficult to learn, either.

00:30:38.769 --> 00:30:41.138
There's been some wonderful
presentations on that in

00:30:41.171 --> 00:30:44.475 align:start size:81% position:19%
other--in meetups
and other WordCamps.

00:30:44.508 --> 00:30:49.680 align:start size:94% position:6%
And so, a lot of times--does
classic editor,

00:30:49.713 --> 00:30:52.850 align:start size:91% position:9%
so those people
who are still on the wire,

00:30:52.883 --> 00:30:55.353
you can still have some
familiarity with that.

00:30:55.386 --> 00:30:58.422 align:start size:91% position:9%
So, it's all these fields
that he needed

00:30:58.455 --> 00:31:00.324
specifically for what he does.

00:31:00.357 --> 00:31:03.828
And then, the page
looks like this.

00:31:03.861 --> 00:31:12.169 align:start size:91% position:9%
So, that is the end of my
talk, and I guess we

00:31:12.202 --> 00:31:14.639
can go for questions now.

00:31:14.672 --> 00:31:16.474
And I got to figure
out what to do here.

00:31:16.507 --> 00:31:18.576 align:start size:88% position:13%
Stop the share.
Is that what I'm doing?

00:31:18.609 --> 00:31:20.077
I think so.

00:31:20.110 --> 00:31:24.749
I just stopped the share.

00:31:24.782 --> 00:31:26.250
Okay.

00:31:26.283 --> 00:31:28.486
So, I can take questions now.

00:31:28.519 --> 00:31:31.088 align:start size:88% position:13%
Joe: All right, Alicia.
Great job.

00:31:31.121 --> 00:31:33.324 align:start size:84% position:16%
The funny thing is,
like, I was--you know,

00:31:33.357 --> 00:31:35.826
I didn't know--you know, I
saw your finishing slide,

00:31:35.859 --> 00:31:37.328 align:start size:88% position:13%
and then you said,
"But it's not the end."

00:31:37.361 --> 00:31:38.863
And I was like, "Oh."

00:31:38.896 --> 00:31:41.198 align:start position:0%
Then you started--then you--so,
you caught me off guard.

00:31:41.231 --> 00:31:42.533 align:start size:91% position:9%
Alicia: Like that--
you know when people clap

00:31:42.566 --> 00:31:44.335
when they're at that last bit?

00:31:44.368 --> 00:31:46.637 align:start size:91% position:9%
And you're like, "Oh,
oh, there was more, oops."

00:31:46.670 --> 00:31:47.905
Joe: Yeah, I apologize.

00:31:47.938 --> 00:31:50.875
One of the great things for the
audience to know about Alicia is

00:31:50.908 --> 00:31:54.578
part of the inspiration and
rebirth that she described.

00:31:54.611 --> 00:31:57.682 align:start size:94% position:6%
I went through the same
thing with our next speaker,

00:31:57.715 --> 00:32:01.719
but the three of us, we got
together a few weeks ago to

00:32:01.752 --> 00:32:05.122
promote this event because we
were so into accessibility.

00:32:05.155 --> 00:32:08.326
And all three of our meetups did
a joint meetup on--it was called

00:32:08.359 --> 00:32:11.329 align:start position:0%
"WordPress Meetup Accessibility
Day," so it's kinda cool

00:32:11.362 --> 00:32:13.264
to see everyone doing it.

00:32:13.297 --> 00:32:15.066
So, let's jump to
the questions here.

00:32:15.099 --> 00:32:16.801
Let me refresh the page.

00:32:16.834 --> 00:32:21.572 align:start position:0%
And again, thanks, everyone,
for--thanks everyone for chiming

00:32:21.605 --> 00:32:26.410
in and being part of
the conversation here.

00:32:26.443 --> 00:32:27.845
All right.

00:32:27.878 --> 00:32:33.084 align:start position:0%
The first question is, "How
does art shape how you develop?"

00:32:33.117 --> 00:32:35.119 align:start size:88% position:13%
Alicia: Oh, how does
art shape how I develop?

00:32:35.152 --> 00:32:36.787
That's why I do it.

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:40.157
Okay, honestly, I was a
fine artist for 15 years,

00:32:40.190 --> 00:32:41.592
and there is a website up.

00:32:41.625 --> 00:32:46.097 align:start size:97% position:3%
And, please, that person
doesn't exist who put that up.

00:32:46.130 --> 00:32:48.866 align:start position:0%
It was an ex-boyfriend, and it's
literally the worst site you

00:32:48.899 --> 00:32:51.435
will ever see on the
website, on the web.

00:32:51.468 --> 00:32:55.306 align:start position:0%
And its, like, technical
aspects--it's aliciastrose.com.

00:32:55.339 --> 00:32:58.743
It's an old HTML site that's
literally--like, you know the

00:32:58.776 --> 00:33:02.413 align:start size:97% position:3%
ones that just kinda like suck
themselves into the corner?

00:33:02.446 --> 00:33:04.682 align:start size:78% position:22%
It's like it
wasn't even--it's

00:33:04.715 --> 00:33:05.883 align:start size:81% position:19%
bad, but my pictures
are on there.

00:33:05.916 --> 00:33:09.220 align:start position:0%
So, I was a fine artist, and
then I would go on the Internet,

00:33:09.253 --> 00:33:10.788 align:start size:94% position:6%
and I'm like, "I don't see a
reason why the Internet

00:33:10.821 --> 00:33:12.590
has to look like this."

00:33:12.623 --> 00:33:16.694 align:start size:97% position:3%
And so then, I just said,
"I'm gonna be a web designer.

00:33:16.727 --> 00:33:19.163
I'm gonna make things beautiful.
That's what I really wanna do."

00:33:19.196 --> 00:33:21.766
And so, I was really, like,
close--I was really concerned

00:33:21.799 --> 00:33:25.436 align:start size:97% position:3%
about the craft and
textures and things like that,

00:33:25.469 --> 00:33:29.340
so art is a huge
part of what I do.

00:33:29.373 --> 00:33:32.276
And I think coding
is an art form too.

00:33:32.309 --> 00:33:35.646 align:start size:94% position:6%
Joe: Oh, that leads into
our next question perfectly.

00:33:35.679 --> 00:33:37.348
We've got that synergy going.

00:33:37.381 --> 00:33:39.784
"What caused a shift towards
accessibility and where do you

00:33:39.817 --> 00:33:43.320 align:start size:88% position:13%
see this shaping
your development work?"

00:33:43.353 --> 00:33:47.091 align:start size:97% position:3%
Alicia: Oh, god, the shift was
definitely that meeting

00:33:47.124 --> 00:33:50.661 align:start size:84% position:16%
that--the meetup
when Sumner showed up.

00:33:50.694 --> 00:33:54.432
I mean, I was already, kind of,
into the headings thing and all

00:33:54.465 --> 00:33:56.834
that stuff and, like,
"Don't use all caps.

00:33:56.867 --> 00:33:59.203
It's screaming," and, you
know, things like that,

00:33:59.236 --> 00:34:01.772 align:start size:81% position:19%
but it was more
leaning toward SEO.

00:34:01.805 --> 00:34:07.211
But then, when I found out that
it violated civil rights--it was

00:34:07.244 --> 00:34:10.181 align:start size:97% position:3%
separate but not equal to put
an overlay, and I had

00:34:10.214 --> 00:34:14.018
one on something that--and
I--took me five minutes.

00:34:14.051 --> 00:34:15.519 align:start size:91% position:9%
I took it off.
I was really--I came back.

00:34:15.552 --> 00:34:18.289
I was like, "I just--"
I was like, "Excuse me.

00:34:18.322 --> 00:34:19.723
I gotta go do something."

00:34:19.756 --> 00:34:21.525
And I came back, and I told her.

00:34:21.558 --> 00:34:24.261
And I was like, "Thank
god I got that off."

00:34:24.294 --> 00:34:28.065
He's well-known in the
community too, and so,

00:34:28.098 --> 00:34:31.502 align:start size:97% position:3%
and I see right now there's no
way it's gonna go back.

00:34:31.535 --> 00:34:38.075 align:start size:97% position:3%
It's just gonna keep expanding
because at this point, the

00:34:38.108 --> 00:34:44.381 align:start size:84% position:16%
Internet's become
quite--it's a resource

00:34:44.414 --> 00:34:47.284 align:start size:91% position:9%
and it's a lifeline,
so--and it's for everyone.

00:34:47.317 --> 00:34:50.821 align:start size:97% position:3%
And not only that, like I--and
on--is that I was

00:34:50.854 --> 00:34:52.723
also on a team called BRCvr.

00:34:52.756 --> 00:34:55.793 align:start position:0%
We were one of the--highly
successful bringing Burning Man

00:34:55.826 --> 00:35:00.164 align:start position:0%
to virtual reality, and they're
even bringing captions into

00:35:00.197 --> 00:35:01.799 align:start size:81% position:19%
virtual reality,
and I had this fun--

00:35:01.832 --> 00:35:04.535
See, what is happening, too,
is because of the exposure to

00:35:04.568 --> 00:35:07.404
people, like the people who
are doing the sessions here,

00:35:07.437 --> 00:35:13.310
like Meryl and then Sumner,
I was in a beta testing in

00:35:13.343 --> 00:35:16.413 align:start size:94% position:6%
this--on one of these
platforms, virtual reality.

00:35:16.446 --> 00:35:20.818 align:start size:94% position:6%
And I asked, "Is there
anyone in here who's deaf?"

00:35:20.851 --> 00:35:23.053
And there wasn't, so
I had to tell 'em,

00:35:23.086 --> 00:35:26.557 align:start size:91% position:9%
"This test probably
isn't gonna be effective.

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:29.426
You know, you have to have
someone who's actually deaf

00:35:29.459 --> 00:35:32.263
to do these things," so.

00:35:32.296 --> 00:35:34.532 align:start size:88% position:13%
Joe: Awesome, all right,
our next question,

00:35:34.565 --> 00:35:37.067 align:start size:94% position:6%
"Having had an active design
business before learning

00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:39.803 align:start position:0%
accessibility, how do
you deal with communicating with

00:35:39.836 --> 00:35:43.040 align:start position:0%
clients when telling them
that something you did for them

00:35:43.073 --> 00:35:46.043 align:start size:91% position:9%
doesn't meet
accessibility standards?"

00:35:46.076 --> 00:35:47.545 align:start size:78% position:22%
Alicia: Oh,
that's easy, guys.

00:35:47.578 --> 00:35:51.248
Don't worry about that one.

00:35:51.281 --> 00:35:54.351 align:start size:84% position:16%
The technology
marches on, I'm sorry.

00:35:54.384 --> 00:35:56.320
It's like we gotta
get with the program.

00:35:56.353 --> 00:35:59.390 align:start size:97% position:3%
I mean, even--a website--okay,
have you ever googled

00:35:59.423 --> 00:36:02.259
lifespan of a website?

00:36:02.292 --> 00:36:05.029
I googled it last year, and
it said five to seven years.

00:36:05.062 --> 00:36:06.363
I googled it yesterday.

00:36:06.396 --> 00:36:09.099 align:start size:84% position:16%
It said three to five,
or three to two.

00:36:09.132 --> 00:36:11.635 align:start size:94% position:6%
The lifespan of the
current design of a website

00:36:11.668 --> 00:36:14.238
is, like, three years.

00:36:14.271 --> 00:36:16.340 align:start size:94% position:6%
They should be thinking
about getting a new website,

00:36:16.373 --> 00:36:22.079 align:start position:0%
even if it's accessible or
not, so this is--a website's not

00:36:22.112 --> 00:36:27.318
something, like, you purchase.

00:36:27.351 --> 00:36:29.720
Like, it's, like, a cheap thing
you get at Kmart, and you think

00:36:29.753 --> 00:36:31.689 align:start position:0%
it's gonna work for you to
make you a whole bunch of money.

00:36:31.722 --> 00:36:34.358 align:start size:97% position:3%
It is a serious thing, and
people have to understand it's

00:36:34.391 --> 00:36:36.727
an investment involved,
and so I really want

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:39.163
that to get imparted too.

00:36:39.196 --> 00:36:40.764
And it's an evolving thing.

00:36:40.797 --> 00:36:44.034 align:start size:88% position:13%
It's not something that
just you make it

00:36:44.067 --> 00:36:45.369
and it sits there and works.

00:36:45.402 --> 00:36:49.373 align:start size:94% position:6%
A website's never finished.
It's never finished.

00:36:49.406 --> 00:36:51.842 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's like an evolving
thing, and

00:36:51.875 --> 00:36:53.043
the content's always changing.

00:36:53.076 --> 00:36:57.248
You always have to be kind
of like--it's like gardening.

00:36:57.281 --> 00:36:59.416
Do you ever finish your garden?

00:36:59.449 --> 00:37:01.318
You don't--garden's done,

00:37:01.351 --> 00:37:03.754 align:start size:91% position:9%
or do you--every
season you're kinda like,

00:37:03.787 --> 00:37:05.556 align:start size:81% position:19%
"I'm gonna grow
these bulbs bigger.

00:37:05.589 --> 00:37:07.057 align:start size:94% position:6%
Or I'm gonna try
something else over there"?

00:37:07.090 --> 00:37:08.291
That's exactly what
a website's like,

00:37:08.325 --> 00:37:10.527
and you shouldn't--your garden
shouldn't be more important than

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:16.133 align:start position:0%
the website that's
supposed to be your livelihood.

00:37:16.166 --> 00:37:19.136
Joe: All right, so we got time
for one more quick question,

00:37:19.169 --> 00:37:21.639 align:start size:97% position:3%
and it's sorta tied into
one of the earlier questions.

00:37:21.672 --> 00:37:27.411
"How has your thinking changed
in terms of your development

00:37:27.444 --> 00:37:30.481
process or your mentoring
business since you've been

00:37:30.514 --> 00:37:32.583
impacted by accessibility?"

00:37:32.616 --> 00:37:35.753 align:start size:97% position:3%
Alicia: Oh, man;
so accessibility is often--is

00:37:35.786 --> 00:37:38.322 align:start size:84% position:16%
always on the
forefront of my mind.

00:37:38.355 --> 00:37:42.459 align:start size:94% position:6%
It's whenever I'm doing
anything, almost every day I

00:37:42.492 --> 00:37:46.597 align:start size:97% position:3%
have some--a conversation or a
little bit of an exchange

00:37:46.630 --> 00:37:48.666
with somebody about something.

00:37:48.699 --> 00:37:52.503
Just recently, there was
a theme that--you know,

00:37:52.536 --> 00:37:54.505 align:start size:94% position:6%
there was--they weren't
underlining the links in the

00:37:54.538 --> 00:37:59.276 align:start size:97% position:3%
admin because they wanted the
experience to be the same

00:37:59.309 --> 00:38:00.544
as the front of the site.

00:38:00.577 --> 00:38:04.682
And my links are underlined, but
they were the same color as the

00:38:04.715 --> 00:38:07.384 align:start size:81% position:19%
content, so the
response was, "Well,

00:38:07.417 --> 00:38:10.287 align:start size:84% position:16%
most people have
different colors, so."

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:13.624
I was like, "No, no, you
gotta keep the underline.

00:38:13.657 --> 00:38:17.094 align:start size:94% position:6%
The underline has got to
stay in the admin, I mean--"

00:38:17.127 --> 00:38:19.229
And then, I got a piece of code,

00:38:19.262 --> 00:38:24.068 align:start position:0%
and it took away all of the
styling of the front-end stuff,

00:38:24.101 --> 00:38:27.004
and so I explained, "That
experience is not the same

00:38:27.037 --> 00:38:31.275 align:start size:78% position:22%
experience that
everyone's getting

00:38:31.308 --> 00:38:33.677
because I wanna be--because
I want it to be accessible.

00:38:33.710 --> 00:38:36.180 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, you have to have--the
experience has to be the same

00:38:36.213 --> 00:38:38.682 align:start position:0%
for everybody, so the
underline should just show up."

00:38:38.715 --> 00:38:40.417
And so, like, there's
just things like that,

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:45.756
so--and so--and I'm always,
like, explaining to people

00:38:45.789 --> 00:38:48.092 align:start size:88% position:13%
a little bit at a time,
especially clients.

00:38:48.125 --> 00:38:50.060
You don't wanna overwhelm them
because then it looks like it's

00:38:50.093 --> 00:38:54.698
too much work and really not.

00:38:54.731 --> 00:38:56.200 align:start size:94% position:6%
Joe: Awesome.
Well, thanks again, Alicia.

00:38:56.233 --> 00:38:58.469 align:start size:91% position:9%
How can people get
you--find you on Twitter?

00:38:58.502 --> 00:39:00.070 align:start size:84% position:16%
Alicia: Oh, okay,
I put it at the end of

00:39:00.103 --> 00:39:04.241
this--on the slides, but it's
IntrepidRealist on Twitter.

00:39:04.274 --> 00:39:07.077 align:start position:0%
Joe: Awesome; well, thanks again
and thanks, everyone,

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:10.514 align:start position:0%
for attending this
session with Alicia and myself.

00:39:10.547 --> 00:39:13.650 align:start size:91% position:9%
You can continue the
conversation on Twitter at

00:39:13.683 --> 00:39:17.321
WordPress Accessibility
Day, #WPAccessibilityDay,

00:39:17.354 --> 00:39:23.394
#WPAD2020, or @WPAccessibility.

00:39:23.427 --> 00:39:26.797 align:start size:84% position:16%
Don't forget to
attend our next talk,

00:39:26.830 --> 00:39:29.433 align:start size:91% position:9%
"The Profitability of
Accessibility" with Sumner

00:39:29.466 --> 00:39:35.072 align:start size:81% position:19%
Davenport at 4 p.m.,
at 4 o'clock UTC,

00:39:35.105 --> 00:39:36.407
here on this same channel.

00:39:36.440 --> 00:39:38.075 align:start size:81% position:19%
See you right
